doc.ContractDescription: WE WILL CONSTRUCT EXTENSIVE MAPS OF THE ULTRAVIOLET (UV) COMPONENT OF THE DUST ABSORPTION IN THE MILKY WAY HALO, USING THE DENSE SAMPLING OF EXTRAGALACTIC QUASARS, AND THE UNPRECEDENTED ULTRAVIOLET SKY COVERAGE OF THE GALEX SATELLITE MISSION. QUASARS ARE SOURCES OF STRONG ULTRAVIOLET FLUX, AND TENS OF THOUSANDS OF VERIFIED QUASARS HAVE BEEN RELIABLY DETECTED IN BOTH GALEX UV BANDS. WHILE THERE IS FAIRLY LARGE INTRINSIC SCATTER IN THE COLORS OF QUASARS, THE MEAN COLORS AT A GIVEN REDSHIFT ARE VERY STABLE, AND SERVE AS A REFERENCE FOR THE QUASAR POPULATION AT ANY LOCATION IN THE SKY. ALSO, THE UNREDDENED ULTRAVIOLET QUASAR SPECTRUM CAN BE RELIABLY ESTIMATED FROM THE OPTICAL SPECTRUM FOR INDIVIDUAL QUASARS, PROVIDING AN EVEN MORE ACCURATE REFERENCE FOR MEASURING UV EXTINCTION. THE ANGULAR VARIATION OF THE PRINCIPAL CHARACTERISTICS OF THE EXTINCTION CURVE FROM OPTICAL TO UV WAVELENGTHS WILL BE MAPPED ACROSS AT LEAST 15,000 SQUARE DEGREES OF HIGH GALACTIC LATITUDE SKY. A PARTICULAR FOCUS OF THIS PROGRAM IS THE SO-CALLED "2175 A BUMP" -- A BROAD DUST ABSORPTION FEATURE IN THE ULTRAVIOLET PART OF THE SPECTRUM. WHILE IT IS A UBIQUITOUS FEATURE IN OUR GALAXY, THE 2175 A BUMP IS APPARENTLY LESS COMMON IN OTHER GALAXIES AND QUASARS. THE DISTRIBUTION OF THE BUMP STRENGTH AND ITS RELATIONSHIP TO OTHER KNOWN STRUCTURES IN THE MILKY WAY WILL PROVIDE TESTS OF THE ORIGIN OF THIS UV FEATURE AND ITS ROLE IN THE EVOLUTION OF THE GALAXY. THIS PROGRAM WILL ALSO PROVIDE INDEPENDENT TESTS OF THE WIDELY USED EXTINCTION MODELS DERIVED FROM OTHER STUDIES, AND EXTEND THE EXTINCTION MODELS TO ULTRAVIOLET WAVELENGTHS. THE RESULTS WILL BE USED TO APPLY BETTER ULTRAVIOLET REDDENING CORRECTIONS TO OBJECTS DETECTED BY UV TELESCOPES, INCLUDING HST, GALEX, AND THE SWIFT UVOT.

doc.ContractDescription: SYMBIOTIC STARS ARE POWERED BY A WHITE DWARF ACCRETING FROM A LATE-TYPE GIANT MASS DONOR. WE NOW KNOW THAT MANY SYMBIOTIC STARS ARE MEDIUM ENERGY (2-10 KEV) X-RAY SOURCES, BUT SOME STAND OUT AS LUMINOUS, HARD SOURCES DETECTED IN THE INTEGRAL AND SWIFT/BAT SURVEYS. THE X-RAYS LIKELY ORIGINATE IN THE ACCRETION DISK BOUNDARY LAYER, AND SO WE EXPECT REFLECTIONS FROM THE WHITE DWARF SURFACE AND DISK. THE HIGHEST TEMPERATURE PLASMA PRESENT IS SET BY THE MASS OF THE ACCRETING WHITE DWARF, AND SO MEASURING THE MAXIMUM TEMPERATURE X-RAY EMITTING GAS ALLOWS US TO SET A LOWER LIMIT THE WHITE DWARF MASS IN THE SYSTEM. WE WILL OBTAIN NUSTAR OBSERVATIONS OF T CRB, A SYMBIOTIC STAR AND RECURRENT NOVA THAT HOSTS A WHITE DWARF THAT IS VERY CLOSE TO THE CHANDRASEKHAR LIMITING MASS OF 1.4 MSOL. WE WILL USE THE X-RAY SPECTRUM AND EXISTING MODELS IN THE XSPEC PACKAGE TO MEASURE THE REFLECTION AMPLITUDE OF THE X-RAY EMISSION, THEREBY IMPROVING OUR MEASUREMENT OF THE MAXIMUM PLASMA TEMPERATURE. THIS WILL IN TURN IMPROVE OUR MEASUREMENT OF THE WHITE DWARF MASS. IDENTIFYING THE MOST MASSIVE WHITE DWARF IN BINARY SYSTEMS IS A KEY STEP IN UNDERSTANDING THE EVOLUTION OF TYPE IA SUPERNOVA PROGENITORS.
